## Use `System.IO.Abstractions` (NuGet)

This is the recommended approach — it's battle-tested and already wraps the full `System.IO` surface.

**1. Install packages:**

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

**2. Register in DI:**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data.txt", new MockFileData("hello") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/existing-dir");

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("hello", service.Load("/data.txt"));
Assert.True(service.EnsureDirectory("/existing-dir"));

service.Save("/out.txt", "world");
Assert.Equal("world", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/out.txt"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**
- Covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, etc. in one package
- `MockFileSystem` provides an in-memory filesystem out of the box
- No need to maintain your own interface/implementation pair

Once you've swapped the constructor parameters, use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill (or do it manually) to bulk-replace the `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your project.
